<!-- Simple function -->
When you type "Alex Developer" in the name field, this code works through several steps to pull the letters "AD" to display on the circular avatar. Here is what each line does, step-by-step:

profile.name.split(' ') This takes the string "Alex Developer" and breaks it into an array of strings by looking for the space characters. Result: ["Alex", "Developer"]
.map(word => word[0]) This goes through every word in that array, and pulls out just the first letter (index 0) of that word. Result: ["A", "D"]
.join('') This glues the letters in the array back together into a single string with no spaces in between them. Result: "AD"
.substring(0, 2) Just in case the user decides to type a massively long name like "Alex Developer The First", we only want to keep the first two characters so the letters actually fit inside the design circle.
.toUpperCase() If the user type something like "alex developer" in lowercase, this forces it to become capitalized so it always looks nice! Result: "AD"
|| '?' If the user deletes everything in the name field (making the name empty), this fallback ensures a ? is displayed in the circle instead of showing an empty blank space!


<!-- Initial variable -->
While it uses several functions to do its job, the block itself is NOT a function.

It is actually a variable assignment.

Here is the breakdown of what is actually happening:

const initials = ...: This makes initials a standard variable (specifically a constant) that just holds a value (like the string "AD"). It is not a function you can call later like initials(). It calculates its value immediately when the component renders.
The Methods (Built-in Functions): .split(), .map(), .join(), .substring(), and .toUpperCase() are all built-in JavaScript functions (specifically called methods because they belong to Strings and Arrays) that you are chaining together to calculate the final string.
The Arrow Function: There is exactly one actual function defined by us inside that block, and it's the arrow function inside the map method: word => word[0].
